Paddy slumped back in the seat. \i "Hah! \i0 We're wanted, we're wanted bad!"\par
Fay said, "There's all space to hide in, a lot of little planets, a lot of big ones. For all anyone knows we might have taken off on a line and be clear out of the cluster by now."\par
Paddy grimaced. "I keep seeing a picture of us hanging by our heels from a post or kicking inside a nerve-suit." He wiped his forehead, ran his hand through his blond bristles. "It gives a man the value of his existence, this life of the hare and the hound. And never a priest to help you into the blessed life to come."\par
"Pish," said Fay. "Confess to me if you want to."\par
"Very well and why not? It's the intent that swashes a man's soul free of guilt. Now then, sister," and Paddy studied the bulkhead, "there was a sin which occurred on the planet Maeve but it's to be supposed I was sorely tempted.\par
"Ah, there's a green garden there at Meran\emdash a terrace where men sit under plane trees and drink the soft mouth-filling beer of the place. Then those soft-eyed girls come swinging by with their shoulders and their long brown legs bare.\par
"They wear pearls in their navels and emeralds in their ears and when they look those long slow looks there's honey in a river between you and all the will for a decent Christian life flits away like gulls down the Bloody Foreland. Now then\emdash "\par
Fay's face twisted in rage and disgust. "A confession? \i Pah! \i0 You're boasting!" She marched across the cabin. "The Shauls are right. Earther savages think of nothing but their glands."\par
"Now, now, my dear\emdash "\par
"I'm not your dear! I'm an Earth Agent, worse luck, and if this weren't the most important thing in my life I'd turn around and head for Earth and put you as far out of my sight and mind as I possibly could!"\par
"Now, now, now. You don't know how lovely you look with your little face all pink with rage."\par
Fay laughed bitterly. "Rage? Not on your life!" She strode to the galley and poured herself a bowl of soup, which she ate with crackers in moody silence.\par
Still turned away from Paddy she said, "We'll be landing in an hour or two."\par
Paddy interpreted the statement as an invitation to join her. Sitting down he chewed reflectively on one of her crackers.\par
"It's a sad responsibility for a pair of fallible humans. ... Now had we old Father O'Toole with us he'd go forth, take the data, hide all in his cassock, come back to the ship and none would dare to interfere."\par
"Father O'Toole is far away," Fay pointed out acidly. "We must cope with this problem ourselves. Though I wish he were here and you were back in Skibbereen. ... We've got a problem which you insist on ignoring. Shaul won't be like Loristan. They've got the brains of the system, the Shauls, and they're oversuspicious."\par
"Hmm." Paddy frowned, drummed the table with his fingers. "If we were journalists when we set down we'd be allowed more freedom with our camera."\par
Fay said grudgingly, "You may be a lecher and a thief but you come up with an idea now and then."\par
They sat a moment in silence. Fay looked suddenly at Paddy with wide eyes. "We'll have to land on the central field, because there's no other. ... We'll have to go through all that uncertainty again, only the Shauls are more careful and thorough. Suppose they take your psychograph?"\par
"Suppose they do?" said Paddy lightly. "Don't you know that I'm three different men? I'm Paddy Blackthorn, the Rapparee, and I'm Patrick Blackthorn, the pride of St. Luke's Seminary, who'll talk you the Greek and the Romish and the Gaelic till your ear shivers for the joy of it, and I'm Patrick Delorcy Blackthorn of Skibbereen, the gentleman farmer and horse-raiser."\par
"There's also Paddy Blackthorn the great lover," suggested Fay.\par
"Right," assented Paddy. "There's four of me and a different psychograph for 'em all. So you see, I've three chances in four to confuse the suspicious devils."\par
"If you do you'll be the first. You can change your fingerprints but you can't change your brain strenuata."\par
The Shauls had sheared off and leveled the peak of an old volcano to make Aevelye's space-field. When Paddy and Fay brought their boat down they found themselves overlooking a vast panorama of badlands, a chopped and hacked region of red, yellow and green-gray rock.\par
Directly below, a tremendous rift rent the planet, a chasm miles across and miles deep. Down one side, on a series of ledges, sat the city Aevelye\emdash white buildings pressed against the walls of the gorge, facing out across the awesome valley.\par
As Almach sank, the light played on wisps of mist hanging in the valley on a level with the rim and the colors were like fantastic music\emdash greens and lavenders, oranges, unbelievable pastels from the reflected and refracted light.\par
The boat came to rest on Aevelye Field\emdash bare and quiet compared to the fields at Badau and Loristan. Fay shivered. "We can't help but be noticed."\par
Paddy looked out the dome. "Here they come\emdash the Cossacks!" He patted Fay's shoulder. "The bold front, now, lass."\par
Four Shaul guards drove up to the ship in a jeep, jumped out. They wore tight sheaths of blue metallic cloth and three carried carbines slung over their shoulders. Their hoods of skin, which they held rigid and stiff, were stained red and painted with indications of rank. The officer, wearing a black star on his hood, climbed up the ladder, rapped smartly on the door.\par
Paddy opened for him without pumping clear the entrance lock and coughed at the acrid dust that followed the Shaul into the cabin.\par
The officer was a young man, very terse and exact. He pulled out a pad of printed forms. "Your papers, please."\par
Fay handed him the ship's license. The officer bent to look.\par
"Albuquerque Field, Earth." He looked up, turned to Paddy, scrutinized him up and down. "Name, please?"\par
"Mr. and Mrs. Joe Smith."\par
"Your business here on Shaul?"\par
"Business and pleasure," Paddy replied jocularly. "We're tourists and journalists at the same time. We've been wanting to make the Big Line, and when we caught the news of the assassination we thought maybe we'd take some pictures around the planet."\par
The officer said without emotion, "Earthers are not in good reputation around the Five Planets."\par
Paddy protested, "Ah now, we're just working people and we've our living to make, whether there's births or deaths or war or peace. And if you'd say a good word for us we'd sure appreciate it"\par
The officer swept the interior of the craft with his eyes. "We don't have too many Earth journalists setting down at Aevelye in these small boats."\par
"Listen now!" said Paddy eagerly. "Then we're the first? There's been none from the Fax Syndicate\emdash that's our competitor?"\par
"No," said the officer coolly. "You're the first." He returned to his printed form. "How long do you plan to stay?"\par
"Oh, maybe a week or until we accomplish our business. Then maybe we'll be on to Loristan or Koto for more."\par
"Ghouls," said the officer under his breath. He handed them an ink-pad. "Your thumbprints please."\par
Gingerly they pressed their identities on his sheet.\par
"Now"\emdash he wrote a moment\emdash "here's a receipt and I'll have to take your power-arm and keys. Your boat is impounded. When you want to leave apply to Room Twelve, Terminal Hall, for a permit."\par
"Here now," protested Paddy. "Isn't this high-handed? Suppose we want to tour across the planet?"\par
"Sorry," said the officer. "There's a state of emergency, and we're bound to take precautions until things are normal again."\par
"Now then," Fay said nervously, "we don't mind a little inconvenience if we get what we want."\par
The officer was copying information from the ship's papers. At last he looked up, produced a pair of small flat boxes.\par
"Here are temporary respirators, which will serve until you buy permanent breathers. Now, please, if you will come with me there's a formality required of all Earthers."\par
"And what's that?" demanded Paddy truculently. "A return to the old closed-space system? I'll have you know I'm a citizen of Earth and Ireland too and\emdash "\par
"I'm sorry," said the officer. "I merely obey orders, which are to pass all Earthers, no matter how innocent, through the psychograph. If you are not a criminal then you need not worry. If you are, then you will be accorded justice."\par
"The psychograph is not an instrument for innocent people," said Paddy. "Why, the indignity of it! I'll leave the planet first and spend my money on Loristan."\par
"Not now," said the officer. "I regret that these are emergency conditions and that certain hardships must be endured. Please follow me."\par
Paddy shrugged. "As you wish. I'll have you know, however, that I protest bitterly."\par
The officer did not reply but stood watching as Paddy and Fay donned their respirators. Fay's mouth drooped, her eyes were moist when they fell on Paddy. Paddy moved with sullen deliberation.\par
The officer gave them seats in the jeep, trundled them to a ramp leading to a hall under the field.\par
"Into Room B, please."\par
In Boom B, they found three other Earthers, two angry old women and a sixteen-year-old boy waiting for their psycho-graphs. One by one they were taken into an inner room to emerge a minute or so later.\par
At last the Shaul nurse beckoned to Fay. "You first, please."\par
She rose, patted Patty's cheek. "I'm sorry it had to end like this," she said softly and disappeared.\par
A moment later the attendant motioned for Paddy.\par
Paddy entered a room, bare except for a desk, a chair and the psychographer. A doctor stood waiting while an orderly in blue metallic military uniform sat by a desk watching a screen with a psychgraph pattern pinned to a board beside it.\par
The doctor looked at Paddy once, then again searchingly. He turned to the orderly. "This one fits the physical data. The face is different, the hair and eyes are different but of course ... Into the chair, please," he said to Paddy.\par
"Just a minute," said Paddy. "Am I a common criminal then?"\par
"That's what we are about to find out," the doctor told him quizzically. "In any event this is merely a routine check."\par
"What's all this?" Paddy motioned to the screen and the psychograph pinned up beside it\emdash a pattern of lines like a weather chart superimposed on a relief map of the Himalayas.\par
"That, my friend," said the doctor imperturbably, "is the psychic pattern of Patrick Blackthorn\emdash and if I may say so it's the oddest pattern I've ever seen. It's unmistakable.\par
"There's little chance of doing anyone injustice. Now if you'll take this seat and let me fit these pick-ups on your head..."\par
"I'll fit 'em," growled Paddy, taking a seat. He jammed the contacts down across his scalp. "Go ahead now and be damned to your bureaucratic nonsense."\par
The doctor snapped a switch. Paddy felt a slight tingling, a momentary drowsiness.\par
"That's all," said the doctor, glancing across to the orderly.\par
"Strange," muttered the orderly. "Come here, doctor..."\par
The doctor stared curiously at Paddy's pattern, shook his head "Strange."\par
"What's strange?" asked Paddy.\par
"Your\emdash ah, pattern. It's hardly typical. You can go. Thank you."\par
Paddy returned to the anteroom, found Fay pacing the floor nervously. She gave a small squeak. \i "Paddy!"\par
\i0 The attendant looked up sharply and Paddy's knees wobbled. Fay's eyes grew large and moist. She blushed red. Taking Paddy's arm she pulled him out into the big echoing lobby.\par
"Paddy," she whispered. "How did you get away? I was waiting with my heart in my mouth, waiting for the shouting and banging\emdash "\par
"Shh," said Paddy. "Not so loud, and I'll tell you a great joke. I was once in a battle and they lifted my scalp. The doctors sewed me up again with a big platinum plate across my sconce. I can laugh at those psychographs, because the metal shorts them all out and they never read the same on me."\par
Fay bristled like a porcupine-fish.\par
"Why didn't you tell me?"\par
Paddy shrugged. "I didn't want to worry you."\par
"Worry\emdash\i Hah! \i0 I'm only worried because now I'll have to live with you another couple of months."\par
"Now, now, my dear," said Paddy abstractedly. He took her arm. "And here is where we get our breathers."\par
