Paddy drew back in indignation. "Faith, now. I'll use my flashlight first. Three hundred marks for a few bits of wire and junk?"\par
There's my labor, lad, and my training. Long years now I've studied."\par
Two hundred fifty marks was the figure finally reached, delivery to be made in two days.\par
Darkness filled the valley outside like pale ink in a vast basin and the slope above was hung with a thousand colored lights\emdash red, green, blue, yellow, all soft and vague as if their purpose were less to illuminate than to decorate.\par
On the terrace outside the hotel Paddy said to Fay, "Do you know, I can feel something of what the first Son loved in this planet Shaul. It's as violent and queer as a madman's whims but the color and now the softness of the night are wonderful. And out there across the valley there's another settlement and the lights glow across to us like fireflies."\par
Fay said softly, "Is it nicer than Skibbereen, Paddy?"\par
"Ah!" sighed Paddy. "And now you've touched me, my dear. When I think of the turf-smoke that they still burn after all these ages and how it comes reeking in from the bog and the old pub around from where I was raised and the River Ilen\emdash yes, I'll be glad to get home."\par
"Then there's always the terrace at Meran," suggested Fay, "with the beer and the women."\par
"Ah!" cried Paddy. "The beer, it's like the nectar of paradise and the girls with their soft hands! If you catch the pearl in their navels with your teeth, then they must do your bidding for as long as you will\emdash that's the custom of Maeve\emdash and some of them wear pearls as big as plums."\par
"If you'll excuse me," said Fay coolly, "I'm going to buy a map and find Corescens. I'll leave you to your reminiscences."\par
"Here now," cried Paddy. "Faith, I was but teasing. And you started me out on it!" But she had disappeared.\par
Next morning they took possession of a rough-steering old sightseeing platform\emdash the proprietor of the rental yard had been reluctant to trust Earthers with anything better\emdash and loading the camera aboard they shoved off and out across the hazy valley.\par
Paddy said, "And now where's Corescens that you studied on last night?"\par
"We've got to find Fumighast Ventrole," said Fay. "It's supposed to be twenty miles north, a dead crater."\par
They rose out of the valley into the blaze of Almach's light and the complex face of Shaul spread out to all sides.\par
Fay pointed. "See that smoke rising? That's the volcano Aureo and just beyond is Corescens."\par
Fumighast Ventrole was another vast chasm in the planet, nearly circular in cross-section and so deep that its bottom could not be distinguished through the haze. The sides glistened and glittered, rays of light flashing and darting in a thousand directions like glass spears\emdash back and forth, reflecting in sprays of pure primitive color, flickering, dazzling as the boat sank on snoring old jets.\par
As they reached the mouth of the gap there was a sudden \i swushhhh \i0 and a guard boat hung alongside.\par
"What's your business?" asked a Shaul with a black star painted on the inside of his hood.\par
"We're journalists from Earth and we want to photograph the home of the dead Son."\par
"Do you have a Decency Certificate from the Office of Rites?"\par
Paddy shoved his head forward. "Decency Certificate? Of course I'm decent, you insolent thrush! And I'll come aboard you in another minute."\par
Fay nudged him. "He means a permit That's their way of speaking."\par
Paddy subsided with ill grace.\par
Fay said cheerily to the corporal, "No, we don't have any permit but all we want to do is take a few pictures."\par
The corporal said stiffly, "I'm sorry but\emdash "\par
A Shaul in civilian dress, standing beside him, muttered into his hood. The corporal stared at Paddy intently, "When did you arrive?"\par
"Yesterday."\par
The corporal dialed a communicator, spoke at some length, nodded. He turned to Fay and Paddy. "The orders are to let you down." Thanks," said Fay.\par
Paddy whispered, "The suspicious devils, they want to trap us and I'll bet you they watch us through telescopes all day."\par
Fay said, "It's a ticklish feeling\emdash almost as if we're trapped in this hole."\par
"Hush now," said Paddy. "There's still the Blackthorn luck on our side."\par
Down into the glistening gap and they saw that the walls were lined with great banks of crystals, hanging like bunches of grapes. As Almach rose in the sky, the colors glanced and twinkled, wove magic nets across the gap, tangled meshes of near-tangible fire. On a ledge a thousand feet below the surface sat a great house, a hall with two wide white-columned wings in a wide garden of the peculiar crystalline plants.\par
Swooping from nowhere the guardship drew alongside again.\par
"As a courtesy due journalists from Earth you have been extended freedom of the house. The bereaved family is not at home but the servants have been instructed to assist you. They will serve you what food and drink you wish."\par
He bowed with sardonic courtesy and the guard-ship rose swiftly as if it had been jerked up by a cable.\par
"Rats in a trap," said Paddy.\par
"Probably they don't suspect us directly," Fay said thoughtfully. "They think we might possibly be some sort of accomplices. They're giving us plenty of rope. Well, we'll worry about it later. It's a chance we have to take."\par
They landed on the terrace amid utter silence. The cool space of the house opened in front of them and through the columns they could see the rich furniture for which the Shauls were famous\emdash chairs of every height and inclination, walls upholstered in peach-colored floss.\par
