XIII\par
\par
\scaps Fay\scaps0 , Fay, Fay!" cried Paddy. "Why didn't you leave the wretched world when you had the chance?"\par
She smiled wanly. "Paddy, I couldn't leave you. I knew I should. I knew my life was more important to Earth than to you. I knew all the things that the Agency drilled into me\emdash  but still I couldn't leave without trying to help. And they trapped the ship."\par
They stood in a wide concrete hall, a hundred yards long, high-ceilinged, illuminated with a glow that seemed blue and yellow at the same time, like strong moonlight.\par
Paddy looked in all directions. "Can they hear us now?"\par
Fay said dully, "I imagine that every sound we make is amplified and recorded."\par
Paddy moved close, and said softly into Fay's ear, "They want to trade us our lives."\par
She looked at him with wide eyes that still held traces of terror. "Paddy\emdash I want to \i live!"\par
\i0 Paddy said between his teeth. "I want you to live too, Fay\emdash and me with you."\par
She said desperately, "Paddy, I've thought the whole thing out. And I don't see what we gain by holding our tongues. The Kotons will get the space-drive\emdash but what then?\par
"Earth wouldn't have it in any event since we've got only four fifths. And the four fifths"\emdash she breathed in his ear in a whisper so low he could hardly hear\emdash "I can dictate from memory."\par
"From\emdash " Paddy gasped.\par
"Yes. I told you once I was trained for that."\par
"Hmm."\par
Fay said softly, "If we were able to keep silent no one would have space-drive. In ten years there's be no more star travel. On the other hand, if we told what we know\emdash and if we can get back to Earth\emdash then Earth will have as much as we have now."\par
"Which is as good as nothing," Paddy said bitterly. "Of the thirty numbers you only know twenty-four. Twenty-four dial-settings."\par
He paused, blinked. A picture came into his mind from a past that seemed remote as ancient Egypt. It was the interior of the manifolding shop on Akhabats, where the five Sons came to curl power into the tungsten cylinders. Five panels, each with three dials.\par
"Fay," said Paddy, "I'm not fit to live."\par
She looked at him in alarm. "What's the matter?"\par
Paddy said slowly, "I see it all now and I see it clear. We've been abysmal fools. I've been the worse one. Now on these sheets"\emdash he leaned to her ear\emdash "remember the duplications?"\par
"Oh, Paddy!"\par
He said, "When I broke into that shop on Akhabats I saw a curling machine. There were fifteen control knobs. Those data sheets show six readings to a sheet\emdash thirty in all. Does that mean anything?"\par
She nodded. "There are duplicates of the numbers too. Paddy\emdash we had it all!"\par
\i "All \i0 of it," said Paddy. "We didn't need to come to Koto any closer than the Southern Cross."\par
Fay winced.\par
"We've got to get away," said Paddy with great energy.\par
"Somehow. Because in that little cap of yours you've got space-drive."\par
Fay shook her head sadly. "They won't let us go, Paddy. Even if we tell everything we know they'd still kill us."\par
"Not till we'd blown the fuses in all their nerve-suits."\par
"Oh Paddy! Let's think-think!"\par
They thought. Paddy said, "He's hot after us, that Zhri Khainga, he's got the wind up. But why? Maybe word has got out to the other planets that he's caught us and all the spies and agents and secret services are going into action and he doesn't want to chance our holding out till the others get to see us."\par
There was a moment of silence. "Think," muttered Fay.\par
"Listen here," said Paddy. "We'll tell him that you'll go out to get the sheets and I'll stay as a hostage. Then you go to Earth and we'll spring the news that we know all there is to know about space-drive. Then you buy me back for twenty space-drives more or less."\par
"At the going rate," said Fay dryly, "that's twenty million marks. Are you worth that much?"\par
"That's the best I can think up," said Paddy. "There's no other way of getting us both out alive and the drive to Earth."\par
"Zhri Khainga won't like it," said Fay. "He'll want us to trust him. After he gets the sheets\emdash\i then \i0 he turns us loose."\par
"I wonder," said Paddy. "What?"\par
"Could it be that he'd agree to all of us going? We'd take him to you-know-where alone\emdash and there we'd switch."\par
Fay said breathlessly, "It would be fair that way and he'd be getting the quick action he seems to want. Let's ask."\par
Stepping gingerly past the ranked crew members, conscious of the oyster-colored gaze, Paddy and Fay entered the familiar cabin which had taken them so far.\par
Zhri Khainga followed them, the port was slammed shut, they were cast adrift from the mother ship. Paddy and Fay stood stiffly, silently by the control deck; Zhri Khainga took a seat back in the cabin and leaned back at his ease.\par
"Now," he said, "I have complied exactly with your conditions. Here is your space-boat\emdash we are alone. Take me to the hiding place of the data, I will call my own vessel, you may leave me and go your way in friendship. I have done my part. See to it that you keep good faith."\par
Paddy looked at Fay, rubbed his nose uneasily. "Well, now, to tell the truth, we'd like to look the ship over. Some of your men\emdash by mistake, I'm saying might be asleep in the bilges or checking stores in the forward locker."\par
Zhri Khainga nodded. "By all means satisfy yourselves. In the meantime," he turned to Fay, "perhaps you will put your ship on course."\par
Wordlessly Fay climbed up into the seat, threw the boat into space-drive and the vessel which had brought them from Koto twinkled an enormous distance astern.\par
Paddy came back. "Nothing," he grumbled. "Not hair nor hide."\par
Zhri Khainga nodded his head sardonically. "It troubles you that I keep to the terms of the bargain?"\par
Paddy muttered under his breath. Fay sat looking into the blank outside the port. Suddenly she pulled back the space-drive arm. The boat surged and sang into normal continuum once more.\par
"Look outside, Paddy," she said. "Around the hull."\par
"That's it," said Paddy. He pulled an air-suit from the rack, stepped in, zipped up the seam, set the bubble on his head while Zhri Khainga watched without words.\par
Paddy vanished outside the lock and Fay waited beside the controls, covertly eyeing the Koton, trying to fathom the weft of plot and plan below the dome of the shaven pate.\par
"I am thinking," said Zhri Khainga, "of great deeds. The wealth of any imagining shall be mine. I will give a quadrant of the planet to the plain of Arma-Geth\emdash it shall be extended.\par
"Mountains will be leveled, the plain will be floored with black glass. So shall the statues dwell in the opulent silence and there will be my magnificent entity among them. I shall be magnified a thousand times. For all eternity will I tower\emdash mine will be the life-loved pivot of history."\par
Fay turned, looked out through the port. Where was Sol? That faint star? Perhaps.\par
Paddy entered the ship. Another figure followed him. In the bubble Fay saw the great-eyed head of a Koton.\par
"This is what I find strapped to the hull. Do you call that subscribing to our proposals?"\par
Zhri Khainga sat upright. "Quiet now, little man! Who are you to challenge my wishes? You should be glorying in your fortune, that you give freely what otherwise could be wrung from your lips." He sat back in his chair. "But now\emdash  we are committed."\par
The Koton who had entered the ship with Paddy had not moved from his first position. Zhri Khainga waved his fingers. "Out. Fly through space with your hands. You are not needed."\par
The Koton hesitated, looked up at Fay, back at the Son of Langtry, slowly turned, let himself out the lock. They saw him push himself away from the ship and drift off alone and hopeless.\par
"Now," said Zhri Khainga, "are you satisfied? We are alone. To the hiding place. Please be swift. There is much of importance awaiting my pleasure throughout the universe. Note that my gun is at hand, that I shall be alert."\par
Paddy slowly joined Fay on the control deck. "Go on, Fay. Set the course."\par
Delta Trianguli shone far and cold to the left. The dull black planet bulked below. Zhri Khainga, at the port, said, "Delta Trianguli Two; am I right?"\par
"You are," said Paddy shortly.\par
"And now where?"\par
"You'll see in due course."\par
Zhri Khainga wordlessly seated himself once more.\par
Paddy went to the transmitter, sent out a call on the frequency used in the air-suit head-sets. "Hello, hello."\par
They listened. Faintly came, "Hello, hello," out of the receiver.\par
Zhri Khainga moved uneasily. "There are others here?"\par
"No," said Paddy. "None but us. Did you get the line, Fay?"\par
"Yes."\par
The dead face of the planet passed below\emdash plains flat and dull as black velvet, the pocked mesh of mountains, which looked as if they had been dug by monstrous moles. Dead ahead rose an enormous peak.\par
"There's Angry Dragon," said Fay.\par
She set the ship down on the plain of black sand. The hum of the generator died, the ship was still.\par
Paddy said to the still-seated Son of Langtry, "Now listen close and don't think to trick us, for sure you'll never win by it. You might get our lives but you'd never hold the four sheets for your own."\par
The Koton stared unblinking.\par
Paddy continued. "I'm going out there, and I'm going for the sheets. They're well hid. You'd never find them."\par
"I could have a hundred thousand slaves on this spot next week," observed the Koton tonelessly.\par
Paddy ignored him. "I'll get the sheets. I'll lay them on that bit of black rock out there. Fay will stay here in the ship. When I set them down you'll call your ship, tell them where to come for you, where to pick you up.\par
"Then you'll get in your air-suit and come toward me and I'll leave the sheets and go to the ship. When we pass each other you'll put down your gun and go on. I'll continue toward the ship and so we'll take our leave. You'll get the sheets and in a day or so your ship will be here to take you home. Is that agreeable?"\par
Zhri Khuinga said, "You allow me little scope for tricking you. You are strong and muscular. When I put down the gun what is to prevent you from attacking me?"\par
Paddy laughed. "That little poison ball-whip you carry along your arm. That's what I'm afraid of. What's to keep you from attacking me?"\par
"The fact that you can outdistance me by running, and thus regain your boat. But how will I know that you are not giving me bogus data sheets?"\par
"You have binoculars," said Paddy. "I'll hold the sheets up for your inspection and you can watch me put them down. They're unmistakable\emdash and with those binoculars you can read every bit of the text."\par
"Very well," said the Koton. "I agree to your conditions."\par
Paddy slipped into his air-suit. Before setting the bubble over his head he turned to the still seated Koton. "Now this is my last word. By no means try to trick us or catch us off guard.\par
"I know you Kotons are devils for your revenges and your tortures and that you love nothing better than blackhanded treachery\emdash so I'm warning you, take care or it will go ill with you and all your hopes."\par
"What is your specific meaning?" inquired the Koton.\par
"Never mind," said Paddy. "And now I'm going."\par
He left the ship. Fay and the Koton could see him through the dome, marching across the black sand toward the peak. He disappeared into the tumble around the base.\par
Minutes passed. He reappeared and Fay saw the glint of the golden sheets.\par
Paddy stood by the black rock, held the sheets up, face toward the space-boat. Zhri Khainga seized his binoculars, clamped the funnel-shaped eye-pieces over his eyes, stared eagerly.\par
He put down the binoculars.\par
"Satisfied?" asked Fay brittlely.\par
"Yes," said the Koton. "I'm satisfied."\par
"Then call your ship."\par
Zhri Khainga slowly went to the space-wave transmitter, snapped the switch, spoke a few short sentences in a language Fay could not understand.\par
"Now, get out," said Fay in a voice she could hardly recognize as her own. "You keep your part of the bargain, we'll keep ours."\par
"There is much yet unsaid," the Koton murmured. "The tale of your insolences, your detestable audacities."\par
Fay's body surprised even herself. Without conscious volition she sprang at Zhri Khainga, snatched the gun. It was hers. Clumsy now, juggling it, fingers shaking, she jumped back. Zhri Khainga gasped, leaned forward, flung out his arm. Poison-filled balls on elastic strips swished an inch from Fay's face.\par
\i "Ahhh!" \i0 she cried. "Get out, now\emdash get \i out! \i0 Or I'll kill you and gladly!"\par
