\par
\scaps Zhri Khainga\scaps0 , his face a strange pasty lavender color, assumed his air-suit. Menaced by his own gun, he backed out of the boat.\par
Paddy had been waiting. Now he stepped forward and the Koton ran out to meet him, bounding, hopping, peculiarly agile.\par
Paddy met him halfway. He paused, expecting the Koton to throw down his gun. The Koton ran past, aching for the golden sheets. Paddy hesitated\emdash then, seeing no gun at the Koton's belt, turned and ran for the boat.\par
Fay let him in, Paddy pulled off the head-bubble, looked at Fay's tense white face. "What is it then, Fay?"\par
"There's no power."\par
Paddy's shoulders sagged and his hands paused at the zipper of the air-suit. "No power?"\par
"We're marooned," she said. "And that Koton ship will be here in a few days\emdash maybe less." She stepped up on the deck, looked out the dome toward the Angry Dragon. "And Zhri Khainga is waiting."\par
"Och," muttered Paddy. "We'd walk out across that black sand and give up our breaths first." He joined her on the control deck. "Are you sure about that power now? I was fooled once myself." He tried the controls. They were dead.\par
Paddy chewed his lip. "That villain worked some sort of relay switch into the drive, that would cut off our energy once we landed. And how he must be gloating!"\par
"Now he's got the sheets," said Fay, "and he can hide from us until his ship comes. We could never find him."\par
"It's rats we're like, on a sinking ship. Try the space-wave, Fay! Send out a call."\par
She flipped the switch. "Dead!"\par
Paddy shuddered. "Don't be using that word so much." He paced, two steps across the deck to port, four steps back to starboard, back to the center of the cabin. "Now try the anti-gravity. That's on its own special unit and there's no connection."\par
Fay slid the metal boss. Their weight left them.\par
"Now," crowed Paddy, "at least we'll leave the planet, for the surface will rotate away from under us."\par
"Zhri Khainga will see us leave," said Fay. "He'll know what we're doing and he'll find us as easily as if we were crawling on our hands and knees in the snow."\par
Paddy reached out, seized a stanchion, squeezed it. "If this were only his neck," he said between his teeth, "I'd hang on while his heels pounded on the deck and laugh in his face."\par
Fay laughed wanly. "This is no time for day-dreaming, Paddy dear." She looked out the port. "We've already risen about a foot from the ground."\par
