"I think I'll just shoot the end of the tube loose and it'll be like breaking open a fire-hose." He looked out the port. "Now we're six feet off the ground\emdash and look! there's that Koton! See him? Sitting there as calm and majestic as you please laughing at us. Here give me that gun, I'll make a Christian of him\emdash and I'll shoot off our tube at the same time."\par
He snapped the bubble back over his head, stepped into the lock, opened the outer port. Zhri Khainga quickly ducked behind a rock and Paddy regretfully held his fire. He turned, braced himself, drew a bead on the tip of the lower tube, gritted his teeth, commended himself to his natal saint and squeezed the trigger.\par
The tube split, an instantaneous spiral of blue flame lashed out, smote the ground. The boat lunged ahead, up at a slant.\par
Fay painfully got down from the elastic webbing, ran to the port. \i "Paddy!" \i0 She looked through the bull's-eye in the lock, heart in her mouth.\par
Paddy lay crumpled, unconscious. The bubble around his head was cracked; air was whistling out\emdash visibly, as the water-vapor condensed to fog. Blood was trickling from his nose, spreading along his face.\par
\i "Paddy!" \i0 cried Fay as if her soul were dissolving. She could not close the outer door as his leg hung out, twisted at an odd angle. She could not open the inner door lest she lose all the air inside the ship.\par
She bent her forehead into the palms of her hands, whimpered. Then rising, she ran to the air-suit rack. One leg\emdash both legs\emdash zip up the side\emdash head-bubble, two snaps. She ran to the lock, tugged it open against the inner pressure and the blast of air nearly flung her out into space.\par
She caught hold of Paddy's arm, pulled his weightless body in against the dying current of air.\par
"Paddy," whispered Fay. "Are you dead?"\par
