Paddy sighed, shook in a delirium. Fay gave him a third injection of vivest-101, and spoke to him soothingly in a voice soft as summer grass.\par
Paddy gave a sudden jerk, then sighed, relaxed. Fay bent over him. "Paddy?" He breathed, he slept.\par
Fay arose went to the port. Delta Trianguli was a small cold ball of light astem, the planet inconspicuous among brighter stars.\par
Three days passed. There had come no cruising shark of a Koton ship. Perhaps they were safe. Perhaps Zhri Khainga preferred the thought of his golden sheets to revenge.\par
Paddy awoke on the fourth day. "Fay," he muttered.\par
"Yes, Paddy dear."\par
"Where are we?"\par
"We're safe, Paddy, I hope."\par
"Still no power?"\par
"Not yet. But I found what happened and we can fix it as soon as you get well. I'm trying to pull it apart\emdash a busbar that was shorted and fused. It made a terrible mess."\par
Paddy lay still a moment. His face twitched, his mouth pulled up at the corners in a grimace. He said, as if to himself, "Whatever happens, it's the Son that did it to himself and his own people. It was his own treachery his own fault, and none of mine...."\par
Fay bent over him anxiously. "What do you mean, Paddy?"\par
Paddy muttered, "I planned all the time to tell him, since I'm no murderer, before he ever used the sheets."\par
"What did you do?"\par
Paddy sighed turned his head away. "There's a wealth of destruction in a dot, Fay\emdash a little dot." Fay peered at his face. Was he asleep? No. "Paddy, what are you talking about?"\par
"Fay," said Paddy weakly, "the space-drive has been my fascination ever since I first heard about it and it's like to been my death\emdash twice, three, four, a dozen times. And one of the times was on Akhabats, where in my ignorance I thought I could burrow into the manifolding shop and curl them out by the dozen.\par
