"So?" asked Fay breathlessly.\par
"So\emdash when Zhri Khainga, the Koton, pulls the switch-all hell will break loose."\par
"But Paddy," whispered Fay, "why? Those were the sheets we got from the dead Sons."\par
"There's two little decimal points that make the difference, Fay. Two little dots. On the Badau and the Loristan sheets, the duplicated numbers. I had just time for it. Two little marks."\par
She straightened from her bent position, looked away.\par
"It was to be our ace in the hole," said Paddy. "Sure I'd have told him about it over space-wave once we got clean away because I'm no hand for the killing, Fay. but now whatever happens is through himself since he cut off our power and it's his hard luck."\par
"It's the ninth day, Paddy," said Fay.\par
"Humph. Two days for the ship to pick him up, four days back to Montras, three days. It should be time for news."\par
He turned on the receiver, functioning feebly from the power of the cell in his flash-light.\par
A Shaul spoke, and they strained their ear to hear.\par
"Attention\emdash word from Zhri Khainga, Son of Langtry from Koto. Paddy Blackthorn, the convict and assassin, has been killed on a dead-planet hide-out by a Koton patrol-ship. No further details have been released. Thus the greatest manhunt in the history of space comes to an end and interstar traffic returns to normal."\par
