"Hush, Paddy dear," said Fay. "You'll excite yourself. Let's get back to our work. In another day we'll be repaired and send a warning message."\par
"Och," said Paddy. "The suspense is killing me. Why doesn't he drop the other shoe?"\par
Exclaimed Paddy, "The news. Fay, it's time for the news."\par
Fay wiped her face with a greasy hand. "If you'd wait ten minutes we'd be done. There's just the clip and welding to be done on that gang-switch, and then we'd get the news on ship's power.\par
Paddy limped unheeding to the receiver and the thin whistle of space-wave sang through the cabin. Then, gong, gong, gong! rang the speaker\emdash deep doleful sounds.\par
In a kind of numb attentiveness they heard the voice. "... stupendous crater ... millions dead ... for the dead Son, Zhri Khainga..."\par
Fay turned off the speaker. "Well, there it is. Don't worry any more. It's done. There goes Zhri Khainga and all his nerve-suits."\par
"I wouldn't have had it that way," said Paddy dully.\par
